o expose them to our &quot;popular&quot; culture of death and greed and expect them to defend their faith.   There are so many great teachers at our public schools, just not screened for what this family considers a priority, and they will never have the freedom to communicate these moral values within our public system.    While I appreciate the need for a “neutral” (if it truly was neutral) public school system, I just wish there was a fully-funded option for us. I didn’t balk at contributing as a taxpayer for 30 years to send our country’s children to school, but the same funding per student at the school I choose for my child would seem reasonable to me.  Why, as taxpayers, do we receive less for our kids? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1007" language="en" documentId="3207" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Yvonne B" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:34PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="11" thumbsDown="0" origId="3207" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1007"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>